{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:56:50.432762", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nObjective: assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root cause(s). No remediation steps are included.\n\nExecutive summary\n- The network is largely functional: core/server networks and most hosts can reach the server farm and DNS/web services. OSPF routes are present and inter-device IP-layer connectivity to the DHCP and DNS/web servers is working from distribution and server routers.\n- A distinct fault affects the entire 10.2.1.0/24 access segment: hosts in that segment are not receiving IP addresses and are therefore unreachable from the rest of the network. Evidence points to a DHCP configuration omission (missing subnet declaration for 10.2.1.0/24) on the central DHCP server as the root cause. L2 connectivity to the distribution router exists; DHCP relay/path to the DHCP server appears functional.\n\nKey evidence and observations (collected from the environment)\n1. Global reachability tests (summary)\n   - Many hosts (10.1.x.x and 10.2.2.x subnets) and servers (10.200.0.x) show successful ping results with low loss.\n   - Several hosts in the 2.1.* naming block have \"unknown\" ping results in the reachability matrix:\n     - host_2_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_2, host_2_1_2_1, host_2_1_2_2 — test results are null/unknown (no ping attempts completed), while other hosts returned OK.\n\n2. Host net configuration (host_2_1_1_1)\n   - ifconfig/ip addr show eth0 is UP and running with link-layer activity but no IPv4 address assigned (no \"inet\" entry).\n   - ifconfig shows RX/TX packets on eth0, confirming L2 connectivity exists between host and switch/router, but host lacks IP configuration (no DHCP lease).\n\n   Extract (summary):\n   - eth0: UP, link present\n   - No IPv4 address shown on the host (only loopback 127.0.0.1 is configured).\n\n3. Distribution router for that access segment (router_dist_2_1)\n   - br0 interface has IP 10.2.1.1/24 (distribution-side interface for that VLAN/subnet) and is UP.\n   - IP routing table includes 10.2.1.0/24 on br0 and OSPF routes to other subnets and 10.200.0.0/24 via core next hops.\n   - router_dist_2_1 can successfully ping the DHCP server (10.200.0.8) — demonstrating IP connectivity/forwarding between the distribution router and DHCP server.\n\n   Extracts (summary):\n   - br0: inet 10.2.1.1/24 (UP)\n   - Routes for server and user subnets via OSPF present\n   - Ping to DHCP server: 0% loss, rtt ~2.8 ms\n\n4. DHCP server configuration (dhcp_server: /etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf)\n   - Subnet declarations present for:\n     - 10.1.1.0/24\n     - 10.1.2.0/24\n     - 10.2.2.0/24\n     - 10.200.0.0/24 (present but commented/pass)\n   - Missing: subnet declaration for 10.2.1.0/24 is not present in dhcpd.conf.\n\n   Extract (relevant lines):\n   - existing: subnet 10.2.2.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 { ... }\n   - no subnet 10.2.1.0 entry.\n\nBehavioral correlation and anomaly detection\n- Hosts in the 10.2.1.0/24 segment (the \"2.1\" naming group) do not have IPv4 addresses (DHCP failure), yet their NICs are up and show L2 traffic — this indicates L2 connectivity to the distribution switch/router is intact.\n- router_dist_2_1 (10.2.1.1) is up and reachable; it can reach the DHCP server. This implies DHCP-relay/path is available and not the point of failure.\n- The DHCP server lacks a subnet declaration for 10.2.1.0/24. When a DHCPDISCOVER is relayed for a network that the server does not have a declaration for, the server will not offer an address for that subnet. That explains why hosts in 10.2.1.x receive no address while other subnets served by the same DHCP server are fine.\n- Reachability results show successful connectivity for other subnets and to the server farm (DNS and web hosts), implying OSPF and router-layer reachability are healthy network-wide.\n\nFault localization\n- Affected endpoints: All hosts in the 10.2.1.0/24 access segment (host_2_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_2, host_2_1_2_1, host_2_1_2_2 — the reachability report had these as \"unknown\").\n- L2 device(s): switch_access_2_1_1 — L2 appears to pass frames (host NIC shows RX/TX), so switch is not clearly failed; it's likely operating but hosts are not getting DHCP addresses.\n- Distribution router: router_dist_2_1 — interface br0 (10.2.1.1) is up and routing; router can reach the DHCP server, so it’s not the cause.\n- DHCP server: dhcp_server — its configuration is missing the 10.2.1.0/24 subnet declaration, which prevents it from assigning addresses to that segment.\n\nRoot cause\n- Primary root cause: DHCP server configuration omission — missing subnet declaration for 10.2.1.0/24. Because the DHCP server has no configured subnet for 10.2.1.0/24, it does not issue leases for that network even when DHCP requests are relayed from the distribution router. The hosts in that access VLAN therefore remain without IPv4 addresses.\n- Contributing/confirming facts:\n  - Hosts on that segment show L2 activity but no IP (consistent with DHCP failure).\n  - router_dist_2_1 has the correct 10.2.1.1/24 address and routes, and can reach the DHCP server; thus, DHCP relay/path is functioning and OSPF/routing are working.\n  - Other subnets receive DHCP leases successfully (dhcp_server contains corresponding subnet entries for them).\n\nImpact assessment\n- Immediate impact: All hosts in the 10.2.1.0/24 access subnet are offline at IP layer — they cannot communicate with servers, DNS, or other hosts (no IP address assigned).\n- Broader network: Core, distribution, server access router, DNS, web servers, load balancer, and other user subnets appear unaffected and reachable.\n- Services: Hosts in the affected subnet cannot use DHCP-based services, cannot resolve/visit web pages, and are isolated at L3 despite L2 connectivity.\n\nAdditional notes / corroborating details\n- DHCP lease parameters on dhcp_server show short lease times (default-lease-time 30; max-lease-time 60) — unrelated to root cause but worth noting operationally (not part of this diagnosis).\n- OSPF routes shown on router_dist_2_1 include the path to 10.200.0.0/24 via core; this corroborates overall routing health.\n- The reachability matrix includes successful pings from the DHCP and DNS servers to other hosts and servers, further indicating central services are reachable except for the affected access segment.\n\nConclusion\n- The network is mostly healthy; the clear anomaly is a DHCP provisioning failure for the 10.2.1.0/24 access network. Localization points to the DHCP server configuration as the primary faulty component (missing subnet entry). Distribution/router and L2 appear operational for the 2.1 segment, and routing/OSPF connectivity to the DHCP server is confirmed.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- show specific logs or packet traces (DHCP relay/requests) to further confirm the DHCP flow, or\n- enumerate which hosts in that segment are unconfigured/impacted, or\n- produce the exact lines from the DHCP server and router showing the relevant config/addresses used for evidence.\n\n(Per instruction, I have not included remediation steps; say if you want remediation recommended.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10232, "output_tokens": 2882, "total_tokens": 13114, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9856}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1088}}}
